data-end="598" data-start="351">In JavaScript, whenever you run a program, the <strong data-end="419" data-start="398">JavaScript engine</strong> (like V8 in Chrome, SpiderMonkey in Firefox, etc.) creates an <strong data-end="503" data-start="482">execution context</strong>.</p><p data-end="598" data-start="351">The <strong data-end="520" data-start="511">first</strong> execution context that is created is called the <strong data-end="597" data-start="569">Global Execution Context</strong>.</p><h2 data-end="790" data-start="760"><strong data-end="790" data-start="763">When is GEC Created?</strong></h2><ul data-end="951" data-start="791"><li data-end="866" data-start="791"><p data-end="866" data-start="793">When you <strong data-end="820" data-start="802">open a webpage</strong> or <strong data-end="839" data-start="824">run JS code</strong> in the browser or Node.js.</p></li><li data-end="902" data-start="867"><p data-end="902" data-start="869">Created <strong data-end="901" data-start="877">before any code runs</strong>.</p></li><li data-end="951" data-start="903"><p data-end="951" data-start="905">It stays <strong data-end="950" data-start="914">alive until the program finishes</strong>.</p></li></ul><div><br></div><div><br></div><p data-end="1034" data-start="982">The <strong data-end="1014" data-start="986">Global Execution Context</strong> has <strong data-end="1033" data-start="1019">two phases</strong>:</p><h3 data-end="1062" data-start="1036"><strong data-end="1062" data-start="1040">(1) Creation Phase</strong></h3><ul data-end="1314" data-start="1063"><li data-end="1099" data-start="1063"><p data-end="1099" data-start="1065">Happens <strong data-end="1083" data-start="1073">before</strong> code execution.</p></li><li data-end="1141" data-start="1100"><p data-end="1141" data-start="1102">JavaScript scans the entire file first.</p></li><li data-end="1198" data-start="1142"><p data-end="1198" data-start="1144">It sets up <strong data-end="1179" data-start="1155">memory for variables</strong> and <strong data-end="1197" data-start="1184">functions</strong>.</p></li><li data-end="1260" data-start="1199"><p data-end="1260" data-start="1201"><strong data-end="1214" data-start="1201">Variables</strong> are hoisted but initialized with <code data-end="1259" data-start="1248">undefined</code>.</p></li><li data-end="1314" data-start="1261"><p data-end="1314" data-start="1263"><strong data-end="1276" data-start="1263">Functions</strong> are hoisted with their complete body.</p></li></ul><div><h3 data-end="1650" data-start="1623"><strong data-end="1650" data-start="1627">(2) Execution Phase</strong></h3><ul data-end="1760" data-start="1651"><li data-end="1689" data-start="1651"><p data-end="1689" data-start="1653">Code actually <strong data-end="1688" data-start="1667">runs line by line</strong>.</p></li><li data-end="1727" div.p: In JavaScript, whenever you run a program, the JavaScript engine (like V8 in Chrome, SpiderMonkey in Firefox, etc.) creates an execution context.
The first execution context that is created is called the Global Execution Context.

li.p: When you open a webpage or run JS code in the browser or Node.js.
It stays alive until the program finishes.

div.p: The Global Execution Context has two phases:

li.p: JavaScript scans the entire file first.
It sets up memory for variables and functions.
Variables are hoisted but initialized with undefined.
Functions are hoisted with their complete body.
Code actually runs line by line.
